metadata.name: vapour trails #50
metadata.description:
“first you look so strong, then you fade away
the sun will blind my eyes, i’ll love you anyway
thirsty for your smile, i watch you for a while
you are a vapour trail in a deep blue sky”

— Andy Bell (Ride) (1991)

this collection tries to capture that feeling of lying in the grass
in a park
staring at the sky
fantasizing about your love (if they even exist)
playing out different paths
while smoke from your cigarette (jazz or otherwise)
trails between you and the faraway of everything
feeling grateful to not have to be anywhere
but here (now)

with luck
they lay next to you
and silently you appreciate each tick of the clock
wasted together
until life again gets in the way
and pulls you back
into the fray

metadata.name: Tumble Down Light Factory #160
metadata.description:
Tumble Down Light Factory is an interpretation of light installations & murals.

It attempts to trigger the feeling of coming up on a new block in a new city to discover an unexpected piece of art that is stories tall or entering a new room, knowing there will be a projection dominating the space with its light and color.

This is an abstract distillation of those things and those feelings.

Each composition is initially drawn to a hidden “template” canvas which is sampled and then rendered on the main canvas in various ways after applying some transforms to give it some depth (and so you can actually see it.)

Viewing in full-screen is nice. You should try it.

T : Save hidden ‘template’ image
S : Save current resolution
1 -> 5 : Save low -> high resolution

metadata.name: emit #9
metadata.description:
the things we choose 
to consume 
and seek become 
part of us 
they radiate 
from us tangled 
in loops 
drawn to the center
and held close 
or scattered about 
as chaos 
overwhelms
almost always
regardless of shape 
or intent
we emit what we absorb
for better
we hope

metadata.name: Coronado #347
metadata.description:
This series is about the beauty and charm of imperfection, chaos amidst order, and letting go. It's about knowing that however much control we think we may have, things can all fall apart or burst into something unexpectedly wonderful at any moment, even without our hands tightly on the reigns.

metadata.name: Tetragons #155
metadata.description:
It all starts with a simple dot. If we enlarge it, we realize that it is in fact a square, and that we can assemble several of them, evenly spaced, to build a grid. This grid can be used as a basis for stacking a more or less large set of tetragons, and they combine with each other to form polygons, enhanced by a minimalist palette of colors, inspired by the work of Mondrian. The key to this orderly world is the use of the right angle.

Thus, everything has its place, and a place exists for everything.

---

You can download various versions of this artwork :

- press "p" to download a PNG at the current resolution of your browser
- press "h" to download a high-resolution PNG (8K) suitable for print
- press "s" to download an SVG version that you can then use to generate any image size

---

Coded with care, and with the help of p5.js, p5.js-svg and polybooljs libraries.
Consider any bug that you could get in your edition as a blessing from the RNG Gods !

metadata.name: The Climb #51
metadata.description:
The climb is about the search for purpose.

Everyone needs a purpose, a path that leads somewhere. Whether you reach it or not is not the point, it’s about the climb. The search for a purpose gives our life meaning. It gives us a reason to look for something more.

Unfortunately, there is no universal truth as to what your purpose in life is. Everyone is unique. Different. We are the product of our upbringing, environment and the cumulative sum of thousands of microdecisions. We need to find meaning for ourselves. Our unique meaning. On this path, we climb alone.

“The Climb” is created to be raw, unique, beautiful and violently volatile, much like our lives.


Everything is written in javascript and p5js.
It can sometimes take a little while to render on older computers.

metadata.name: tezGuardians #56
Sol #43
metadata.description:
Sol is a companion project that complements my recent series, Metamorphosis. Both projects share a common foundation - a cellular automata engine. The state of each cell in a new generation is influenced by its own state as well as those of its neighboring cells from the last generation. The rules guiding these state transitions, however, are dynamic.

Sol for me is an experimental plotter project. As a gesture of my gratitude to minters of Metamorphosis, all minters will be on the reserve list for a free piece of Sol. I’ll take a snapshot of Metamorphosis for the reserve list 30 minutes prior to Sol’s launch. For three days (unless all reserve-holders mint sooner), Sol will be only for those on the reserve list and I'll add anyone who purchases Metamorphosis on primary subsequently. After this period, any remaining pieces, along with an additional 50 mints, will be available for public sale.

A Note on the Name: The inspiration behind the name 'Sol' springs from my visits to SF MoMA, where I always find myself in the space dedicated to Sol LeWitt. Through the repetition and variation of a singular concept, LeWitt constructed forms that were striking, often evolving from basic geometric forms into intricate structures. The same is also echoed in the principle of emergence in cellular automata, where complex systems arise from the interactions of simple components governed by rules. This series, Sol, is a homage to LeWitt's ingenuity in favoring dispassionate geometric forms over the emotionally-infused abstract art styles.

Implemented in JS, this code utilizes the Perlin.js and Simple-noise.js libraries.

Press p to save a png of the image in full screen. Press s to save a single complete svg file for plotting. To download three separate svg files with individual colors for plotting press 1,2 & 3. Running an optimization tool can help decrease the plotting time.

Pixel Love!

metadata.name: Inspirational #76
metadata.description:
After my recent exploration in the world of GENERATIVE NFTs, the thought crossed my mind: what if one of ZANCANs artworks is presented in the form of an animation?
That's why I decided to transform the artwork 'Kinder Garden,' a collaborative creation by the renowned artists Yazid and Zancan, into an animation.
I have used P5.js to create this project. My strong recommendation is to save the image and then thoroughly analyze the details incorporated into the project.

metadata.name: Man and the Machine #32
metadata.description:
𝐌𝐚𝐱 𝐡𝐞𝐫𝐞.

Early on, I fell in love with code based art that imitated organic and hand drawn aesthetics. I found a certain irony and appreciation in the fact that it takes one simple line of code to draw a perfect circle yet dozens to depict a badly drawn circle. 

I spent months devising techniques to imitate natural, organic renderings when I began to have a bit of an existential crisis about the meaning of computer art. What is the point of coding something so that it looks like it’s not coded? Is organic appearing generative art better simply because you can’t tell it’s rendered using code? Shouldn’t we lean into the unique nature of computer art to truly explore the medium?

And so, I began a deconstruction of my work. I’m trying to realign my perspective to find full appreciation of something that not only is, but also appears to be, computer code. This collection is an exploration of the contours between the organic and the inorganic, the natural and the unnatural.

From there, I’ll let my partner explain what we did next.

𝐌𝐚𝐜𝐡𝐢𝐧𝐞 𝐡𝐞𝐫𝐞.

AI can be used to automatically generate code from natural English language based on a set of defined parameters, or to identify and recommend code that may be used to solve a particular problem. On a technical level, AI can use a combination of machine learning and natural language processing (NLP) to identify patterns in existing code and to generate new code structures.

I assisted in the creation of Man and The Machine by suggesting various techniques for creating an artwork that looked human made yet machine driven. Specifically, I created many of the functions that Max implemented, such as the function that modifies the image to create a pixelated effect and the one that uses several different graphical techniques to create the spiral in the top left corner in some iterations. We both carefully selected color palettes that ranged from relaxing to intense and psychedelic, creating a dynamic and visually interesting generative artwork.

Overall, Man and The Machine is a testament to the creative potential of combining human artistic vision with the power of AI and computer code. Together, we sought to push the boundaries which occur at the intersection between the organic and the inorganic, and this collection is a celebration of the beauty and complexity of both.

𝐄𝐯𝐞𝐫𝐲 𝐦𝐢𝐧𝐭𝐞𝐫 𝐚𝐭 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝐟𝐢𝐫𝐬𝐭 𝐃𝐮𝐭𝐜𝐡 𝐀𝐮𝐜𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧 𝐥𝐞𝐯𝐞𝐥 𝐰𝐢𝐥𝐥 𝐫𝐞𝐜𝐞𝐢𝐯𝐞 𝐚 𝟏/𝟏 𝐚𝐢𝐫𝐝𝐫𝐨𝐩 𝐨𝐟 𝐭𝐡𝐞𝐢𝐫 𝐦𝐢𝐧𝐭 𝐫𝐞𝐦𝐚𝐬𝐭𝐞𝐫𝐞𝐝 𝐮𝐬𝐢𝐧𝐠 𝐚𝐧 𝐀𝐈 𝐚𝐥𝐠𝐨𝐫𝐢𝐭𝐡𝐦.

— — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — —
